1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:02,927
Subs created by: David Coleman.

2
00:00:02,928 --> 00:00:04,788
Hmm.

3
00:00:04,796 --> 00:00:08,340
Check out this letter to the editor.

4
00:00:08,341 --> 00:00:12,046
Apparently, you're not the only guy
who thinks big media and big business

5
00:00:12,047 --> 00:00:14,244
are crushing the
humanity out of humanity.

6
00:00:14,245 --> 00:00:16,645
I'm gonna crush the humanity out
of you if you don't stop talking.

7
00:00:16,646 --> 00:00:20,031
No, seriously. Sounds like
you on one of your rants.

8
00:00:20,032 --> 00:00:21,397
Listen to this.

9
00:00:21,398 --> 00:00:25,434
"When you devote not even a single
page to anything other than your"

10
00:00:25,435 --> 00:00:30,477
"slavishly fawning so-called 'news ',
pandering to corporate advertisers,"

11
00:00:30,478 --> 00:00:36,378
"you destroy all hope of tomorrow
for honest, hardworking Americans".

12
00:00:37,544 --> 00:00:40,050
"Wow! How intriguing, Max".

13
00:00:40,051 --> 00:00:42,529
"Thank you for sharing something
you thought would interest me".

14
00:00:42,530 --> 00:00:44,883
"Oh, and thank you so
much for the papaya".

15
00:00:44,884 --> 00:00:46,353
"It's delicious".

16
00:00:46,354 --> 00:00:50,554
Actually, it could use a little lime.

17
00:00:51,183 --> 00:00:52,892
You know what?

18
00:00:52,893 --> 00:00:54,293
Get it yourself.

19
00:00:54,294 --> 00:00:56,362
- I beg your pardon?
- You heard me.

20
00:00:56,363 --> 00:01:01,588
And as of right now, your
assistant is officially on strike.

21
00:01:01,589 --> 00:01:04,199
If this is about a raise,
you might want to consider

22
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:06,062
a slightly less melodramatic approach.

23
00:01:06,063 --> 00:01:07,961
It's not about the money, Doc.

24
00:01:07,962 --> 00:01:09,821
It's about the working conditions.

25
00:01:09,822 --> 00:01:13,679
Okay, it's about you showing
me a little common courtesy.

26
00:01:13,680 --> 00:01:16,315
What are you.. Lewicki!

27
00:01:16,316 --> 00:01:21,416
All right, all right.
I'll read the damn letter.

28
00:01:34,898 --> 00:01:36,505
Who are you?

29
00:01:36,506 --> 00:01:41,065
Oh, uh, I'm afraid my identity
is classified, old boy.

30
00:01:41,066 --> 00:01:44,246
You're a hallucination.

31
00:01:44,460 --> 00:01:49,907
Whose assistance you'll require if you
have any hope of cracking that code.

32
00:01:49,908 --> 00:01:51,316
What code?

33
00:01:51,317 --> 00:01:53,806
Come now, old boy.

34
00:01:53,807 --> 00:01:57,307
Surely you noticed the awkward syntax.

35
00:01:57,308 --> 00:02:01,268
"Slavishly fawning so-called news"?

36
00:02:02,054 --> 00:02:06,632
Clearly the words have been twisted
around some sort of hidden message.

37
00:02:06,633 --> 00:02:10,353
- Holy sh..
- There's my boy.

38
00:02:10,721 --> 00:02:12,438
It's steganography.

39
00:02:12,439 --> 00:02:14,640
Hidden writing. Look.

40
00:02:14,641 --> 00:02:18,477
If you read every 10th
word, look what you get.

41
00:02:18,478 --> 00:02:20,143
"You'll be proud of me".

42
00:02:20,144 --> 00:02:24,765
"Front-page news tomorrow.
One down, four to go".

43
00:02:24,766 --> 00:02:27,438
"The butcher told me where to start".

44
00:02:27,439 --> 00:02:29,218
It's how The French
Resistance communicated

45
00:02:29,219 --> 00:02:31,100
with British Intelligence
during World War II..

46
00:02:31,101 --> 00:02:33,659
With messages in the newspaper,
right where anybody could see.

47
00:02:33,660 --> 00:02:35,478
French resistance?

48
00:02:35,479 --> 00:02:36,571
Wow.

49
00:02:36,572 --> 00:02:40,365
Meanwhile, back on the plane of
reality, some of us have work to do.

50
00:02:40,366 --> 00:02:42,237
Think about it, Kate.

51
00:02:42,238 --> 00:02:44,003
What ends up on the front page?

52
00:02:44,004 --> 00:02:46,107
- World news, politics..
- Or crime.

53
00:02:46,108 --> 00:02:49,327
I'm guessing whoever wrote this is
sending a message to an accomplice.

54
00:02:49,328 --> 00:02:51,088
"One down, four to go".. That could be..

55
00:02:51,089 --> 00:02:53,456
What? Banks to rob
or victims to butcher.

56
00:02:53,457 --> 00:02:56,990
Do you think that this might be you..

57
00:02:56,991 --> 00:03:00,612
Making connections where
possibly there aren't any?

58
00:03:00,613 --> 00:03:02,849
What are the chances of every 10th word

59
00:03:02,850 --> 00:03:04,885
in some random piece of
text making this much sense?

60
00:03:04,886 --> 00:03:07,072
Or it could be something
completely innocent.

61
00:03:07,073 --> 00:03:09,528
Then why hide it in a code?

62
00:03:09,529 --> 00:03:11,373
Look at the guy's name.. James Smith.

63
00:03:11,374 --> 00:03:13,381
It's got to be the most
common name in America.

64
00:03:13,382 --> 00:03:14,655
It's obviously an alias.

65
00:03:14,656 --> 00:03:17,884
And why use an alias unless
you're doing something illicit?

66
00:03:17,885 --> 00:03:20,419
All right, look, the letter
probably came in via e-mail.

67
00:03:20,420 --> 00:03:22,097
There might be some
way to trace the I.P.

68
00:03:22,098 --> 00:03:24,376
But it could be from an
Internet cafe in Singapore.

69
00:03:24,377 --> 00:03:26,662
You're actually taking this seriously?

70
00:03:26,663 --> 00:03:30,103
I want to be there when you tell
the boss that we're taking on a case

71
00:03:30,104 --> 00:03:35,205
that Dr. Strange found with
his secret decoder ring.

72
00:03:35,206 --> 00:03:37,306
Moretti.

73
00:03:37,745 --> 00:03:39,003
What?

74
00:03:39,004 --> 00:03:41,730
Okay, we'll be right there.

75
00:03:41,731 --> 00:03:45,324
That was the CPD. They need our help
with a possible terrorist attack.

76
00:03:45,325 --> 00:03:48,801
A lawyer downtown opened up a package
and got sprayed in the face with Sarin.

77
00:03:48,802 --> 00:03:50,803
Died before paramedics got there.

78
00:03:50,804 --> 00:03:55,197
Of course, a lawyer, because the
butcher told him where to start.

79
00:03:55,198 --> 00:03:56,509
What the hell are you talking about?

80
00:03:56,510 --> 00:03:58,844
It's Shakespeare.. "Henry VI, part 2".

81
00:03:58,845 --> 00:04:02,898
Dick the butcher says, "first thing
we do, let's kill all the lawyers".

82
00:04:02,899 --> 00:04:04,965
A Sarin attack.

83
00:04:04,966 --> 00:04:09,346
That sounds like front-page news to me.

84
00:04:16,521 --> 00:04:21,118
Normally, I open Mr.
Scantlin's mail myself,

85
00:04:21,119 --> 00:04:23,569
but there was a box marked "personal".

86
00:04:23,570 --> 00:04:27,656
And, he thought someone sent him
a present, so he opened it himself.

87
00:04:27,657 --> 00:04:31,079
And there was a pop, like a firecracker,

88
00:04:31,080 --> 00:04:33,893
and some kind of spray came out.

89
00:04:33,894 --> 00:04:35,528
And he started twitching.

90
00:04:35,529 --> 00:04:37,449
I tried to help him but..

91
00:04:37,450 --> 00:04:39,644
There's nothing you could
have done, Miss Benowitz.

92
00:04:39,645 --> 00:04:42,285
Sarin is more toxic than cyanide.

93
00:04:42,286 --> 00:04:46,636
Can you think of anybody who
might have had a reason to do this?

94
00:04:46,637 --> 00:04:49,906
Tom was a mensch. Everybody loved him.

95
00:04:49,907 --> 00:04:53,917
But he was a trial lawyer.
He won a lot of cases.

96
00:04:53,918 --> 00:04:57,688
I mean, the.. The losers weren't happy.

97
00:04:57,689 --> 00:05:01,083
There is nothing on the package.
No prints, no return address.

98
00:05:01,084 --> 00:05:04,191
All right, well, we'll talk to his
friends, relatives, acquaintances,

99
00:05:04,192 --> 00:05:06,631
but I think we should
start with his case files.

100
00:05:06,632 --> 00:05:08,899
Farrington v. Awakama Sushi.

101
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:12,843
Scantlin got Awakama for 7 mil
for a single case of E. Coli.

102
00:05:12,844 --> 00:05:14,034
Here's something.

103
00:05:14,035 --> 00:05:15,791
Miller v. Klausner extermination.

104
00:05:15,792 --> 00:05:20,572
Klausner was ordered to pay $70,000 in
medical expenses, $1.4 million punitive.

105
00:05:20,573 --> 00:05:22,170
This could be our guy.

106
00:05:22,171 --> 00:05:23,644
Why him out of all these cases?

107
00:05:23,645 --> 00:05:27,654
Sarin's a nerve Agent, but it was
originally developed as a pesticide.

108
00:05:27,655 --> 00:05:29,038
An exterminator would have everything he

109
00:05:29,039 --> 00:05:32,185
needed to mix up a
batch, right on the shelf.

110
00:05:32,186 --> 00:05:35,322
Yeah. I hate Tom Scantlin.

111
00:05:35,323 --> 00:05:37,190
I built my business from nothing.

112
00:05:37,191 --> 00:05:40,152
32 trucks, 58 employees.

113
00:05:40,153 --> 00:05:42,642
Contracts with every school
district in the County.

114
00:05:42,643 --> 00:05:45,336
Not bad for a guy who never
got past eighth grade, huh?

115
00:05:45,337 --> 00:05:47,577
And that S.O.B. took it all away.

116
00:05:47,578 --> 00:05:50,459
Actually, it was a jury of your
peers who decided against you.

117
00:05:50,460 --> 00:05:52,139
They decided wrong.

118
00:05:52,140 --> 00:05:55,208
LBJ Elementary had roaches
the size of chipmunks.

119
00:05:55,209 --> 00:05:59,023
So my guys sprayed with a very reliable
pesticide I imported from Mexico.

120
00:05:59,024 --> 00:06:02,416
Which you had to do because it
wasn't yet approved here in the U.S.

121
00:06:02,417 --> 00:06:04,130
They use that stuff
like ketchup on fries

122
00:06:04,131 --> 00:06:05,834
South of the border,
and no one's complaining.

123
00:06:05,835 --> 00:06:08,000
Someone North of the
border sure complained.

124
00:06:08,001 --> 00:06:10,428
One kid cries sick,
and his parents get a

125
00:06:10,429 --> 00:06:14,022
fast-talking lawyer who
sues the crap out of me.

126
00:06:14,023 --> 00:06:15,639
On the news, he made it sound like I

127
00:06:15,640 --> 00:06:20,380
deliberately set out to
poison schoolchildren.

128
00:06:22,105 --> 00:06:24,866
You know, it's funny that
you should mention the news,

129
00:06:24,867 --> 00:06:27,714
because there was a letter
to the editor in today's paper

130
00:06:27,715 --> 00:06:31,311
about how the media is
stacked against the little guy.

131
00:06:31,312 --> 00:06:34,477
You might find it interesting.

132
00:06:34,478 --> 00:06:36,144
Go ahead. Read it.

133
00:06:36,145 --> 00:06:38,384
Sorry, I don't have my reading glasses.

134
00:06:38,385 --> 00:06:39,756
Maybe you don't need
to read it because you

135
00:06:39,757 --> 00:06:41,669
already know what it
says because you wrote it.

136
00:06:41,670 --> 00:06:44,324
What are you talking about? I
don't write letters to the papers.

137
00:06:44,325 --> 00:06:47,214
Listen, just because I hated Scantlin
doesn't mean that I killed him.

138
00:06:47,215 --> 00:06:53,115
Sorry to interrupt. I wanted to
offer Mr. Klausner reading glasses.

139
00:06:55,666 --> 00:06:58,705
Yeah, uh, I probably got
a different prescription.

140
00:06:58,706 --> 00:07:00,707
All right. I think I
understand what's going on.

141
00:07:00,708 --> 00:07:04,264
Do.. Do you have Dyslexia, Mr. Klausner?

142
00:07:04,265 --> 00:07:05,666
How did you..

143
00:07:05,667 --> 00:07:07,749
It would help explain why a man
as smart as you didn't make it

144
00:07:07,750 --> 00:07:10,306
past eighth grade, and why you
don't want to read the letter.

145
00:07:10,307 --> 00:07:11,957
It's nothing to be ashamed of.

146
00:07:11,958 --> 00:07:13,386
It just means you're not our man.

147
00:07:13,387 --> 00:07:16,322
Just because he's dyslexic
doesn't mean he's innocent.

148
00:07:16,323 --> 00:07:19,774
Probert, for him, words and
letters swim around the page.

149
00:07:19,775 --> 00:07:22,348
So, sadly, he avoids reading
and writing altogether.

150
00:07:22,349 --> 00:07:25,538
It's not like he suddenly woke up one
morning and decided to start communicating

151
00:07:25,539 --> 00:07:28,787
by constructing elaborate codes
buried inside letters to the editor.

152
00:07:28,788 --> 00:07:33,154
So it's back to the
needle-in-a-haystack strategy.

153
00:07:33,155 --> 00:07:35,267
Actually, I've been thinking.

154
00:07:35,268 --> 00:07:39,561
There may be a way to get
the needle to come to us.

155
00:07:39,562 --> 00:07:43,834
In his code, the killer
says, "you'll be proud of me".

156
00:07:43,835 --> 00:07:45,807
He's looking for approval.

157
00:07:45,808 --> 00:07:47,638
If I write him back,
tell him what a great

158
00:07:47,639 --> 00:07:50,104
job I think he's doing,
maybe he'll talk to me.

159
00:07:50,105 --> 00:07:52,872
You plan on making
friends with this lunatic?

160
00:07:52,873 --> 00:07:55,309
We're peas in a pod.

161
00:07:55,310 --> 00:07:59,673
"You think you have guts, but all
I hear is whining and self-pity".

162
00:07:59,674 --> 00:08:02,058
What are you trying to do, get
him to Sarin-gas the whole city?

163
00:08:02,059 --> 00:08:03,804
I thought this was
supposed to be a fan letter.

164
00:08:03,805 --> 00:08:05,604
Have you considered
requesting a new partner?

165
00:08:05,605 --> 00:08:07,194
You're just trying to
get his attention, right?

166
00:08:07,195 --> 00:08:11,068
Exactly. If he's as smart as I think
he is, he'll see the hidden message.

167
00:08:11,069 --> 00:08:14,429
Every 10 words, you said?

168
00:08:15,415 --> 00:08:17,088
"Great move".

169
00:08:17,089 --> 00:08:20,509
"I wish I had your guts".

170
00:08:21,538 --> 00:08:23,939
"Just one question".

171
00:08:23,940 --> 00:08:29,460
"Out of all the lying,
cheating lawyers, why that one?"

172
00:08:30,158 --> 00:08:33,758
"Your friend, kindred spirit".

173
00:08:34,084 --> 00:08:35,603
"Kindred spirit". I like that.

174
00:08:35,604 --> 00:08:40,008
We should rush a copy of this to the paper
so they can get it in tomorrow's edition.

175
00:08:40,009 --> 00:08:42,275
Maybe we could bring it over
there in a horse and buggy.

176
00:08:42,276 --> 00:08:43,781
Is that supposed to be funny?

177
00:08:43,782 --> 00:08:45,615
Listen, papers have online editions.

178
00:08:45,616 --> 00:08:51,516
I'm just gonna post this as a
comment to the original letter, okay?

179
00:08:54,857 --> 00:08:57,463
Maybe he's not checking the comments.

180
00:08:57,464 --> 00:08:59,424
Maybe he doesn't even own a computer.
You know, maybe he's like me.

181
00:08:59,425 --> 00:09:02,395
Some people still like the feel
of a newspaper in their hands.

182
00:09:02,396 --> 00:09:04,513
What are you, a Luddite?

183
00:09:04,514 --> 00:09:06,805
The Luddites were onto something.

184
00:09:06,806 --> 00:09:09,472
You know, studies have shown that
people who spend too much time online

185
00:09:09,473 --> 00:09:11,534
lose the ability to
identify simple emotions

186
00:09:11,535 --> 00:09:14,308
expressed in photographs of human faces.

187
00:09:14,309 --> 00:09:16,559
I mean, computers may be the
greatest technological advance

188
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:18,637
of the last 100 years, but
this whole Internet thing is..

189
00:09:18,638 --> 00:09:22,849
Invaluable in making instantaneous
contact at crucial times?

190
00:09:22,850 --> 00:09:24,851
He answered? What did he say?

191
00:09:24,852 --> 00:09:27,584
"Hey, kindred spirit. Glad
to know I'm not alone".

192
00:09:27,585 --> 00:09:31,215
"You'll get your answer tomorrow
when the next bastard gets his mail".

193
00:09:31,216 --> 00:09:34,694
"But if you're as smart as I think you
are, you can be there when it happens".

194
00:09:34,695 --> 00:09:37,128
What the hell is that?

195
00:09:37,129 --> 00:09:39,011
It's another cipher.

196
00:09:39,012 --> 00:09:41,240
He wants to make sure I'm the
only one that gets the message.

197
00:09:41,241 --> 00:09:43,370
Can you decipher it?

198
00:09:43,371 --> 00:09:46,371
That's a nasty one.

199
00:09:50,020 --> 00:09:52,589
And it's only, what?

200
00:09:52,590 --> 00:09:57,510
Six hours before the
morning post comes 'round.

201
00:09:58,035 --> 00:10:02,295
Not sure if we can crack it in time.

202
00:10:08,873 --> 00:10:11,273
No. No. No.

203
00:10:11,862 --> 00:10:13,699
It's not a Vigenère sequence.

204
00:10:13,700 --> 00:10:15,893
And it's not a polyalphabetic
substitution, either.

205
00:10:15,894 --> 00:10:17,196
What the hell is that?

206
00:10:17,197 --> 00:10:19,797
What difference does it
make if it's not what it is?

207
00:10:19,798 --> 00:10:22,832
Traced the I.P. address the
guy used to send the reply from.

208
00:10:22,833 --> 00:10:23,998
Came up empty.

209
00:10:23,999 --> 00:10:25,836
Code breakers at the NSA
come up with anything?

210
00:10:25,837 --> 00:10:28,080
Nothing yet.

211
00:10:28,081 --> 00:10:31,154
Well, then he better hurry up,
because the Chicago postal workers

212
00:10:31,155 --> 00:10:32,933
are about to have their morning coffee!

213
00:10:32,934 --> 00:10:36,264
Yeah, do you not think I'm
excruciatingly aware of that?

214
00:10:36,265 --> 00:10:37,762
I can't.. Don't.. I can't..

215
00:10:37,763 --> 00:10:42,983
I can't do this with
everybody hovering around me.

216
00:10:44,084 --> 00:10:46,605
What are you doing here?

217
00:10:46,606 --> 00:10:49,527
Thought you could use
a little bit of help.

218
00:10:49,528 --> 00:10:51,891
Yeah, you've been a big help.

219
00:10:51,892 --> 00:10:54,592
What fun is there playing a game

220
00:10:54,593 --> 00:10:57,599
if the other fellow hasn't
got a sporting chance?

221
00:10:57,600 --> 00:11:00,988
You're talking in riddles.
I have enough of those.

222
00:11:00,989 --> 00:11:04,489
I'm simply saying it wouldn't be
cricket for this fellow to write

223
00:11:04,490 --> 00:11:08,930
a code without sending along at
least a hint of how to crack it.

224
00:11:08,931 --> 00:11:12,715
You think the killer hid a
key within the code itself.

225
00:11:12,716 --> 00:11:15,103
Well, if he had..

226
00:11:15,104 --> 00:11:18,584
He'd likely open with it..

227
00:11:18,823 --> 00:11:21,283
Wouldn't he?

228
00:11:23,500 --> 00:11:27,040
Look at the numbers, Pierce.

229
00:11:27,806 --> 00:11:31,706
Look very closely at the numbers.

230
00:11:35,348 --> 00:11:40,808
What is the relationship
between the groups of figures?

231
00:11:42,603 --> 00:11:44,763
14, 41..

232
00:11:45,412 --> 00:11:47,872
No. 144. 12.

233
00:11:48,276 --> 00:11:51,046
144 is the square of 12.

234
00:11:51,047 --> 00:11:52,663
225 is the square of 15.

235
00:11:52,664 --> 00:11:54,608
Squares and their roots.

236
00:11:54,609 --> 00:11:58,328
Well, that's got to mean something.

237
00:11:58,329 --> 00:12:00,937
What? What? Square.. Square roots.

238
00:12:00,938 --> 00:12:02,179
Squares.

239
00:12:02,180 --> 00:12:04,578
N.. Not "root" like a potato.

240
00:12:04,579 --> 00:12:07,939
A Route.. Like a highway!

241
00:12:07,961 --> 00:12:10,282
It's a Route cipher.
Squares and their roots..

242
00:12:10,283 --> 00:12:11,341
The numbers were the tell.

